metadata.name: The Seventh Circle: Meditative: Generative
metadata.description:
The Seventh Circle

"Now I would have you know: the other time / that I descended into lower Hell, / this mass of boulders had not yet collapsed."

The canvas is split into between 64 and 256 areas. Each area is separated from its neighbours by a border of between 1.5% and 4.5% of the canvas.

Each area is further subdivided into between 64 and 100 smaller squares. These are separated by a proportionally-smaller border.

A time-based function affects the hue of each square, mapping the sin and cosine of each squares position, offset by an amount determined from the initial hash. Over time, the colour of the squares will change, dependent on further initial values.

Occasionally, sections of each grid will break away, rendering at an angle to the main piece. Within this, individual squares may be rotated slightly.

The overlaid texture may be dark or bright, horizontally or vertically. The texture size may vary according to the initial conditions.

Most importantly, with the fullness of time, all pieces have a chance of returning to wholeness; they are all a part of a cycle of life, that each one may know its place.

metadata.name: Turbulence
metadata.description:
Swirly shapes are rendered by passes of poisson samples of a warped noise field. The noise shifts with each pass, creating a layered effect. 

Dense editions may take over 2 minutes to draw fully.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.

Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. Image size is 928x1200px
Press ’p’ to pause/resume at any time during the drawing.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a not 1:1 variation of your edition at a resolution up to 3,000 px.

Common:
- 43 set palettes plus many more with combinations
- 3 color distribution methods
- 50/50 dark
- 50/50 monochrome with bright highlights 
- 3 drawing styles: lines, points, colored pencils
- 5 noises effects: full screen, distance from center, distance from bottom, horizontal center, vertical center, random circles, 3,5, or 7 horizontal and vertical bars
- Poisson point distribution based on set layers or the noise value

Rare
- 15% chance of a dark monochrome with gold strands

Copyright (c) 2022 Matt Perkins, hello@mattperkins.me, @nudoru on Twitter. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Untitled 1
metadata.description:
It is fascinating how some simple laws can create beautiful and a large variety of outputs.
At its core, this project uses a collision detection system between a particle and a wall.
I expanded on this idea and placed some rectangles (hidden), generated some balls (particles) and let the laws of motion and symmetry take control. After a little work on how to portray the trajectories, the final piece is in front of you.
Even if you don't mint, I hope you hit refresh enough times to see the variety of the artwork.
Press 's' to save as png

metadata.name: More Sketches of a Drunk
metadata.description:
Hot on the heals of the sold-out "Sketches of a Drunk" comes the next iteration...

"More Sketches of a Drunk" expands upon the previous work. Two new color palettes have been added with vibrant and muted variations of each palette. A dual-layered grid adds to the complexity of each piece which still maintaining it minimalist feel.

My "Sketches of a Drunk" series is a homage to my sketchbooks, chalkboards and scraps of paper that I fill when a few drinks get my creative juices flowing.

I hope you enjoy viewing them as much as I have enjoyed creating them.

metadata.name: Frozen Roses
metadata.description:
Each Frozen Rose is a unique, looping, generative animation.

Frozen Roses uses an underlying pattern of voronoi cells generated from a rotating pattern of points. The differences in these initial patterns of points result in a wide variety of unique shapes and structures. The voronoi pattern is then fed into a series of shaders designed with a user-guided evolutionary process to produce the final animations.

metadata.name: kaleidoscope
metadata.description:
The art is  supposed to be reflective of a nostalgic childhood concept that i now am viewing with some form of maturity.

ka·lei·do·scope | \ kə-ˈlī-də-ˌskōp  \
Definition 
1: an instrument containing loose bits of colored material (such as glass or plastic) between two flat plates and two plane mirrors so placed that changes of position of the bits of material are reflected in an endless variety of patterns
2: something resembling a kaleidoscope: such as
a: a variegated changing pattern or scene
     a kaleidoscope of colors
b: a succession of changing phases or actions
     a kaleidoscope of changing fashions

I have used the concept of the kaleidoscope to visualize the Japanese world view of wabi-sabi. Wabi-sabi is a world view centered around acceptance of the transient and imperfection. The aesthetic is described as one of appreciating beauty that is "imperfect, impermanent, and incomplete". The inner workings of a kaleidoscope are comprised of pieces of shattered glass that, when tumble together and viewed through a prism, form beautiful patterns. Therefore I think the kaleidoscope articulates the idea of wabi-sabi by capturing the ephemeral beauty arising from the collapse of imperfect objects/images.

We are all kaleidoscopes; aside from the obvious comparison to inner beauty and individuality, we are all uniquely complicated on the inside. A mixture of thoughts, ideas, and colors seeing the outside as a reflection of what is on the inside.


By @trp_chai 

March 4 2022 

Made with p5.js and <3 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: Mobius Blocks
metadata.description:
Mobius Blocks is an algorithm that generates 3d stoner sculptures for fun in the metaverse.  It models a mobius strip using randomly generated parameters, and uses that base geometry to host a field of colored boxes.  Pattern, texture, and relief is created by programmatically varying each box’s color and rotation in the field.

Created by @capnganj - one love <3

metadata.name: Distribution for Ukraine
metadata.description:
This is a fundraising piece to support victims of the Ukraine invasion.

100% of proceedings will go directly to a smart contract that will direct the funds to a list of NGOs operating in Ukraine, as suggested by The Giving Block (@TheGivingBlock). The contract has been set up as an initiative proposed by @Veqtor (@VersumOfficial) and @Ciphrd (@fx_hash_).

You can also send donations directly in Tezos to the smart contract (**only tezos**, not tokens). The smart contract address is:
KT1DWnLiUkNtAQDErXxudFEH63JC6mqg3HEx

The source code for the contract is here:
https://github.com/ciphrd/public-contracts/blob/master/donations_ukraine.py

The list of NGOs is here:
https://twitter.com/TheGivingBlock/status/1496910223034155008

The program generates blurring and shifting of various distributions of the input image pixels changed with the alternator depend on numbers given by the hash. Random color of the white square input image stroke is the source of all color values.  Polydiagonal multiplier: the shape of the fractal {0, 1, 2, 4, …, 256}
Segmentation: {on, off}
Subdivision movement: {up, stable, down} Angle: {-45°, 0°, 45°} Side: {left, right} Direction: {left, right} Alternator module: every which value of the input image tones is changed to 0 {2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7}
Gear: the number of extra blur and alternator per frame {1, 2, 3}  

Thanks for collecting
Proembrion 03-04-2022

metadata.name: Dope 90s
metadata.description:
I started the 90s as a dorky-looking kid with giant glasses playing with MacPaint on my dad’s Apple Macintosh. I went on to learn how to program on TI-80 calculators where I made my first generative art... a single line bouncing around the screen. Later I did my first audio visualizations using the unforgettable Winamp software. This project is inspired by and dedicated to those amazing times in the 90s.

Loads of color/shape/gradient rarities that are randomized on mint.

This project was written by Dean Cheesman using p5js.

metadata.name: Machine Spirit
metadata.description:
Machine Spirit picks up where Equilibrium and Equanimity left off. Notwithstanding my love for generative mountains, trees, and (especially) cities, my personal artistic quest remains to produce an algorithm that generates convincing abstract art in the style of Richter and Rothko. The project you are looking at is my best attempt yet.

Trigger warning: some iterations produce rapidly flashing colors which may pose a risk of seizure to people with photosensitive epilepsy or similar conditions.

While the final result is a static image, the live view visualizes how the image is generated. It goes something like this: you start with a grid of cells in random colors, and you feed that into a carefully customized cellular automaton, where the color of each cell is determined by the color of that cell and its neighbours in the previous generation. If you end up with a single color over-powering all the others, or too many different fragmented colors, you start over. But when you reach a stable state with two or three colors, you have achieved your goal: a mathematical balance in color and composition that tends to be aesthetically pleasing as well. You then select a suitable canvas color and run a more computationally intensive rendering process, which makes the end result look more like physical paint on canvas, while retaining the subtle traces of its digital origins.

Press [b]leed, [c]anvas or [d]ensity in the live view to cycle through variations, or [p]rint to save a high resolution capture.

All iterations eventually converge to a stable state, but in theory this could last arbitrarily long, and on rare occasions it may take longer than 5 minutes, in which case the captured preview will be different from the final result. This artwork is fully generative and was hand-coded in 7,500 characters of plain JavaScript code. I didn't use any libraries, but I did take inspiration from an essay by Tyler Hobbs on polygon deformation techniques.

Forever limited to 250 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I truly hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.

All iterations eventually converge to a stable state, but in theory this could last arbitrarily long, and on rare occasions it may take longer than 5 minutes, in which case the captured preview will be different from the final result. This artwork is fully generative and was hand-coded in 7,500 characters of plain JavaScript code. I didn't use any libraries, but I did take inspiration from an essay by Tyler Hobbs on polygon deformation techniques.

Forever limited to 250 editions on the Tezos blockchain. I truly hope you will enjoy yours. London, March 2022.

metadata.name: Strands
metadata.description:
A generative art project inspired by the nature of peace.
Sit back and relax to the motion of falling strands.

This piece starts out as a static display then animates after 5 seconds.

Strand count is random between 20% of the canvas width and 10.
Background rarity: 50% black , 50% white.
Strand color rarity: 5% rainbow, 10% black, 10% white, 25% red, 25% green, 25% blue.

Created with vanilla JavaScript.

All art sold is dedicated to the men and women who served in the US Military. Proceeds go to support veterans and their families.

metadata.name: filter (physical postcards)
metadata.description:
Each minted iteration includes a 1/1 plotter-drawn physical postcard (10x15 cm / 4x6 inches) sent anywhere in the world as letter post.

The colors of the iteration determine the colors for the ink and paper that will be used for the postcard. I use heavy-weight archival paper and all inks are archival as well. 

Since this project was developed to be plotted, it may not look its best at smaller screen sizes or on mobile devices. Use the live view mode on a bigger screen for the best viewing experience. The plotted postcard will probably look slightly different than what you see on screen, because the line-width probably won't be exactly the same, and the colors might also look a bit different. 
 
To get your postcard, simply send me your address and your iteration number as a DM on twitter. I respect your privacy, and won't share your name/address with anyone.

Please note that you can't claim a postcard if you already listed your iteration for sale.

After you send me your address, it might take me a couple of weeks to plot and send your postcard (depending, of course, on how many people claim their postcards at once). Please be patient. I'll let you know when I send it. Follow me on twitter for any updates/news on the project.
 
All postcards will be sent through postal service as regular letter post with no tracking. They will be posted in a regular stamped envelope with some cardboard padding added for protection. This is both to keep the price affordable and to prevent any issues with customs. It is also the authentic postcard experience. But it also means that, depending on where you live, it might take a couple of months before your postcard arrives. Please be patient. I'm located in Germany, so collectors in Europe will probably get their cards faster. If you're willing to pay an additional fee, I can also send your card as a parcel with a tracking number and in better packaging.

---

If you're purchasing this on the secondary market:

Before purchasing, please check the link:
filterfx.carrd.co 
for information on which postcards have been already claimed, and try to get one which still has the postcard available, because if the previous owner hasn't claimed a postcard, you can still get a free postcard. 

If you purchased an iteration where the previous owner has already claimed the postcard: sorry, you can't have a postcard of that iteration, because there can be one of each postcard. But you can contact me and I'll make sure you get a physical postcard from my next postcard-related project.

---

All postcards should be claimed until 31 December 2022.



thresfold, March 2022
made with p5.js

metadata.name: Shortcut
metadata.description:
Animated. Taking a Shortcut through time and space, you find yourself in an infinitely looping wormhole with fellow travelers as company.

[SPACE] to play/pause animation.

Features and Probabilities:
Hue: 49/600 chance for each of 12 hues; 1/50 chance for black and white.
Hue Variability: 49/100 low; 49/100 high; 1/50 none (for black and white).
Brightness: 1/2 low; 1/2 high.
Traffic: 1/3 low; 1/3 medium; 1/3 high.
